{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T17:52:16.801Z",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Neural networks learn by adjusting weights to reduce loss. Backpropagation is the algorithm that computes how much each weight contributed to the error—efficiently, for networks with millions of parameters. Every autograd system in PyTorch and TensorFlow implements this idea."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Backpropagation",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (backprop) applies the chain rule of calculus to compute gradients of the loss with respect to every weight, working backward from the output layer to the input. It requires a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "computational graph",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " recording how each operation (matrix multiply, activation, loss) transformed tensors during the forward pass."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLMs have billions of parameters—manual gradient derivation is impossible. Frameworks run forward pass, compute loss, call "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "loss.backward()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", and populate "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ".grad",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " on each parameter. Fine-tuning, LoRA, and custom training loops all depend on correct gradient flow. Understanding backprop explains vanishing/exploding gradients, why certain architectures use residuals, and why some layers freeze during transfer learning."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forward pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Input flows through layers; each operation builds graph nodes. Final output is compared to targets via the loss function, producing a scalar L."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Backward pass"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Starting from "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "dL/dL = 1",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", gradients propagate backward. If "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "y = f(x)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "L",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " depends on "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "y",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", then "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "dL/dx = (dL/dy) * (dy/dx)",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Matrix operations have well-known gradient rules (e.g., gradient w.r.t. weights involves outer product of input activations and upstream gradient)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Autograd in practice"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\nx = torch.tensor([2.0], requires_grad=True)\ny = x ** 2 + 3 * x\ny.backward()\nprint(x.grad)  # tensor([7.])  because dy/dx = 2x + 3 at x=2"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "model = nn.Linear(3, 1)\nx = torch.randn(4, 3)\ntarget = torch.randn(4, 1)\n\nloss = nn.MSELoss()(model(x), target)\nloss.backward()\n\nfor name, param in model.named_parameters():\n    print(name, param.grad.shape)  # grad same shape as param"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Multi-layer chain"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In a 32-layer transformer, backprop traverses all layers in reverse. Each layer passes gradient to the previous layer's output and accumulates gradient for its own weights. Residual connections add a shortcut so gradient can flow directly backward, mitigating vanishing gradients."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Examples"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Manual two-layer network"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "W1 = torch.randn(4, 3, requires_grad=True)\nW2 = torch.randn(1, 4, requires_grad=True)\nx = torch.randn(3)\n\nh = torch.relu(W1 @ x)\ny = W2 @ h\nloss = (y - 1.0) ** 2\n\nloss.backward()\n# W2.grad, W1.grad now populated"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Gradient flow check"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def grad_norm(model):\n    total = 0.0\n    for p in model.parameters():\n        if p.grad is not None:\n            total += p.grad.data.norm(2).item() ** 2\n    return total ** 0.5\n\nloss.backward()\nprint(grad_norm(model))  # watch for near-zero or huge values"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Memory",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — storing activations for backward pass increases memory; gradient checkpointing recomputes activations to save VRAM at compute cost."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Vanishing gradients",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — repeated small derivatives (sigmoid saturation) shrink signal in early layers; ReLU and residuals help."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Exploding gradients",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — gradients grow unbounded; gradient clipping (max norm) stabilizes LLM training."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Frozen layers",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — setting requires_grad=False skips gradient computation for those parameters, saving memory and compute during partial fine-tuning."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Forgetting zero_grad()",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — gradients accumulate by default; stale grads from prior steps corrupt updates."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Backward on non-scalar loss without reduction",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — backward() expects a scalar; use .mean() or .sum() explicitly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "In-place operations breaking the graph",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — in-place ops on tensors needed for grad can silently fail or error; prefer out-of-place when unsure."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Detaching when not intended",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — .detach() or torch.no_grad() stops gradient flow—correct for inference, fatal mid-training if misapplied."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Standard loop: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "zero_grad() → forward → loss → backward() → optimizer.step()",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use gradient clipping ("
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ") for RNNs and large transformers."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Monitor gradient norms and weight norms alongside loss."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "For inference or evaluation, wrap code in "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "with torch.no_grad():",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " to save memory."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mental model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Forward pass is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "cause and effect",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": inputs ripple through operations to produce a prediction. Backward pass is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "blame assignment",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": the loss asks \"who moved the needle?\" and assigns fractional responsibility backward through every operation. Each weight learns whether it should increase or decrease to shrink future loss."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Backprop applies the chain rule efficiently over the computational graph."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Autograd (loss.backward()) automates this for arbitrary architectures including LLMs."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Always zero gradients before each training step."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Vanishing/exploding gradients shape architecture choices (ReLU, residuals, clipping)."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "torch.no_grad() for inference; requires_grad controls what trains."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
